revision.text:
'''''Choraku-ji Tenmangū''''' (長楽寺天満宮) Tenmangu Shrine is a [[:en:Tenmangu|Tenmangu]] located in Okinawa This appears to be the Choraku-ji in question<ref>[https://shukuken.com/tyorakuji-guide 長楽寺（京都市東山区）の見どころ | 宿坊研究会]</ref> == ChatGPT analysis of the Japanese text == The ''Tenmangu'' shrine, affiliated with ''Choraku-ji'' (長楽寺), is mentioned in the ''Ryukyu Shinto-ki'' (琉球神道記) of 1608, but it was not one of the seven shrines that were designated as ''Taisha'' (grand shrines). Here is what is explicitly stated about ''Tenmangu'' in the text: # '''Listing in the 1608 ''Ryukyu Shinto-ki''''' ''Tenmangu'' (天満宮) is included in the listing of shrines at the beginning of Volume 5 of ''Ryukyu Shinto-ki''. It is associated with ''Choraku-ji'' (長楽寺). However, while seven shrines were designated as ''Taisha'', ''Tenmangu'' was not among them. # '''Possible Origins and Influence''' #* ''Tenmangu'' was likely established under the influence of the worship of Sugawara no Michizane, a scholar and deity of learning venerated in Japan. #* The mention of ''Tenmangu'' suggests a presence of ''Tenjin'' worship in Ryukyu, reflecting the cultural transmission of Japanese religious practices. #* Some records indicate that certain deities were absorbed into Ryukyuan beliefs with additional functions beyond their original roles. In this context, ''Tenmangu'' could have been venerated differently from the typical ''Tenjin'' shrines found in mainland Japan. # '''Broader Context in Religious Evolution''' #* The exclusion of ''Tenmangu'' from the seven grand shrines might indicate that it did not receive the same level of royal patronage as others. #* The later religious transformations and reorganizations of Ryukyu's religious institutions, particularly under Satsuma's influence after the 1609 invasion, may have contributed to its differing status. #* The temple ''Choraku-ji'', which was associated with ''Tenmangu'', is noted in the ''Ryukyu Koku Yuraiki'' (琉球国由来記), suggesting that some shrines and temples had functions adapted to local religious practices. Would you like further research into specific historical records about this ''Tenmangu'' in Okinawa? == Overview == Additionally, among the seven shrines listed as major shrines in the "Ryukyu Shinto Record," {{ill|Yomochi and Ukishima Shrines|lt=Yomochi and Ukishima Shrines|lt=Chojugu Shrine|ja|長寿宮|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chojugu Shrine|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} (later {{ill|Yomochi and Ukishima Shrines|lt=Yomochi and Ukishima Shrines|lt=Ukishima Shrine|ja|浮島神社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ukishima Shrine|qq=}}) and {{ill|Choraku-ji Tenmangū|ja|長楽寺天満宮|sn|天満宮|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Choraku-ji Tenmangū|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, which are not of the {{nihongo|Seike|聖家|qq=}} lineage, are excluded from the kanpei-sha.{{sfn|加治順人|2000|pp=70-73|qq=}}。 The Ryukyu Eight Shrines are {{ill|Naminoue Shrine|en|Naminoue Shrine|qid=Q704636|lt=Naminoue Shrine|1=Naminoue Shrine}}, {{ill|Oki-no-gū‎|ja|沖宮|1=Oki-no-gū‎|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Oki-no-gū‎|13=User:Immanuelle/Oki-no-gū‎|qq=}}, {{ill|Hachiman shrine|en|Hachiman shrine|qid=Q11390939|lt=Asato-Hachimangū‎|1=Hachiman shrine}}, {{ill|Shikina-gū|ja|識名宮|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikina-gū|qq=}}, {{ill|Sueyoshi-gū|ja|末吉宮|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sueyoshi-gū|qq=}}, {{ill|Ameku-gū|ja|天久宮|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ameku-gū|qq=}}, {{ill|Futemma-gū|ja|普天満宮|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Futemma-gū|qq=}}, and {{ill|Kin-gū|ja|金武宮|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kin-gū|qq=}}. All of them belong to the {{nihongo|Seike|聖家|qq=}} lineage. However, since Kin-gū did not have a shrine building or priests and did not receive maintenance funds from the royal government, there is a theory that the other seven shrines are considered kanpei-sha{{sfn|鳥越憲三郎|1965|pp=589-596|qq=}}{{sfn|加治順人|2000|pp=67-70|qq=}}{{sfn|新垣裕之|2021|pp=70-73|qq=}}。 In mainland Japan, many {{ill|Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines|lt=Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines|lt=Kanpei-sha|ja|官幣社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/kanpei-sha|qq=}} shrines are associated with the imperial family or powerful clans through blood relations or ancestral ties. However, in Ryukyu, which had an imported religion, there are no such traditions. It is also characteristic that the establishment tales of the Ryukyu Eight Shrines often involve some kind of spiritual phenomenon.{{sfn|加治順人|2000|pp=70-73|qq=}}。 == Content taken from [https://shinto.miraheze.org/wiki/History_of_Shinto_Shrines_in_Okinawa?oldid=135194 History of Shinto Shrines in Okinawa] == After the {{ill|Invasion of Ryukyu|en|Invasion of Ryukyu|qid=Q1140134|lt=Invasion of Ryukyu|1=Invasion of Ryukyu}} in 1609, shrines of the {{nihongo|Seike|聖家|qq=}} lineage began to receive more favorable treatment. {{Sfn|加治順人|2000|qq=}} For example, until the 16th century, prayers at the royal court were performed by Noro organizations led by {{ill|Kikoe-ōgimi|en|Kikoe-ōgimi|qid=Q11611193|lt=Kikoe-ōgimi|1=Kikoe-ōgimi}} and Zen temples, but after the invasion of the Satsuma domain, prayers for bountiful harvests were carried out by Noro organizations, prayers for the good health of the royal family and the peace of the nation were carried out by {{nihongo|Seike|聖家|qq=}} shrines such as Naminoue-gu and Futenma-gu, and royal funerals and ancestral memorial services were carried out by Zen temples. In addition, in {{ill|Shō Hō|en|Shō Hō|qid=Q1041365|lt=1625|1=Shō Hō}}, it became customary to visit the {{nihongo|Seike|聖家|qq=}} shrines in addition to the Zen temples and Chinese shrines as a {{ill|Shō Ken|en|Shō Ken|qid=Q1061074|lt=11|1=Shō Ken}} Year's event, and in 1644, the king's visit to Futenma-gu Shrine (Hutinma-mee) became a regular event, attracting the reverence of ordinary people as well. {{Sfn|加治順人|2000|qq=}} In 1671, the head priest of Gokoku-ji Temple, Yorimichi, requested {{ill|Shō Shōken|en|Shō Shōken|qid=Q843010|lt=Shō Shōken|1=Shō Shōken}} to convert the Rinzai sect temples Manju-ji Temple (Sueyoshi-gu Shrine), Jin'o-ji Temple (Shikina-gu Shrine), and Seigen-ji Temple (Ameku-gu Shrine) to Shingon Buddhism. {{Sfn|加治順人|2000|qq=}} {{Sfn|新垣裕之|2021|qq=}} It is believed that through these events, the {{nihongo|Seike|聖家|qq=}} shrines became {{ill|Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines|lt=Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines|lt=Kanpei-sha|8=en|10=ja|11=官幣社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/kanpei-sha|qq=}}, and {{ill|the Eight Ryukyu Shrines|8=en|10=ja|11=琉球八社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/the Eight Ryukyu Shrines|1=Eight Ryukyu Shrines|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11573652}} were established. {{Sfn|鳥越憲三郎|1965|qq=}} {{Sfn|加治順人|2000|qq=}} {{Sfn|新垣裕之|2021|qq=}} ==References== <references group="Note"/><references /> {{Okinawan Shrines|qq=}}
